lse, "mention": "Na+", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9986498951911926, "span": {"begin": 461, "end": 464}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:476"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Na+/K+ ATPase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9858247637748718, "span": {"begin": 461, "end": 474}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29103"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "K+", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994851350784302, "span": {"begin": 465, "end": 467}}, {"id": ["mesh:D012964"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "sodium", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992096424102783, "span": {"begin": 504, "end": 510}}], "text": "Sodium potassium adenosine triphosphatase (Na+/K+ ATPase) activity has been studied via electrophysical studies of the movement of ions across membranes. Consistently across freshwater fish taxa, Na+/K+ ATPase occurs as a transmembrane protein, with an understood mechanism of using energy from adenosine triphosphate to move sodium across membranes against its electrochemical gradient. Through toxicant and inhibitor studies, evidence shows that decreases in Na+/K+ ATPase activity result in decreased sodium uptake across gills.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:13:34 +0000 2026"}